{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487414"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:10:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:10:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"344"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/344"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.04,0.38,0.07,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93119"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/344"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76472"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2418"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16366"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31971"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93119"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-woman presents to outpatient gastroenterology with an 18 month history of difficulty in swallowing. She is now only able to managed a semi-solid diet, but is able to maintain her weight. She has a longstanding history of gastro-oesophageal reflux, for which she takes over-the-counter antacids. Whilst she used to get regular and frequent episodes of heartburn, these have become less troublesome, over the last few months. She has a 20-pack year smoking history and enjoys several glasses of wine a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her vital signs are within normal limits and no abnormalities are found. A contrast study is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoma of the oesophagus","Para-oesophageal hernia","Peptic stricture","Corkscrew oesophagus","Achalasia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe contrast study shows a small Type I (sliding) hiatus hernia extending up to a smooth-surfaced narrowed area. Contrast has accumulated above the stricture. This hernia would encourage free acid reflux and without adequate acid suppression, a \u003Cstrong\u003Epeptic stricture\u003C/strong\u003E could easily develop - as it did in this case. The observation that her reflux symptoms have lessened would be consistent with progression of the stricture now limiting reflux.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarcinoma of the oesophagus \u003C/strong\u003Emust be excluded, the chronicity of symptoms tends to lean away from that diagnosis. In addition, the smooth nature of the stricture is more suggestive of a benign cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA true \u003Cstrong\u003Epara-oesophageal (Type II) hernia \u003C/strong\u003Eoccurs when part of the (proximal) stomach herniates through the diaphragmatic hiatus, leaving the cardio-oesophageal junction below the diaphragm. These patients do not necessary get symptoms of gastro-oesophageal reflux. They are uncommon, compared with the Type III, or mixed hernia where a section of proximal stomach lies along side the oesophagus, with the cardio-oesophageal junction above the diaphragm - and reflux being a common symptom.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst the initial appearances of the contrast study might suggest \u003Cstrong\u003Eachalasia\u003C/strong\u003E, with hold-up of contrast - the point of hold-up is far above the diaphragm, making such a diagnosis less likely. Also the patient complains of heartburn and not regurgitation - the latter being characteristic of achalasia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E corkscrew oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E is a radiological term to describe the tortuosity and sacculations that can occur with long-standing motility disorders.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["With the efficiency of proton pump inhibitors in suppressing acid secretions, peptic strictures are now uncommon."],"references":["Bredenoord AJ, Pandolfino JE, Smout AJPC. Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Lancet 2013; 381:1933-42. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(12)62171-0/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76472"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"344"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14415"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14415"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/303cde7a-1fb0-47d7-abae-a440d594e125.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/303cde7a-1fb0-47d7-abae-a440d594e125.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":309,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76472"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T17:06:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T17:06:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"344"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93119"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":